This all feels like shouting into the ether, like none of this ranting will be heard by anyone. I can imagine that if I were saying the exact same things on the Senate floor, as a member of the body, that it would feel much the same.

If civilian arms manufacturers HAD to transition into making other engineered goods, they’d do it.

But it wouldn’t be profitable, so it won’t happen.
The idea that the skill and ingenuity that is applied to the firearms industry couldn’t be shifted into more beneficial sectors is absurd and I refuse to believe it.

This isn’t even getting into the thousands more children who have been traumatized by shootings, either by fear of them or direct experience. Each of them is another individual reduced to a statistic that nobody keeps track of.

School shootings are a unique failure of our society in America, but rather than make a radical shift away from an obsessive and romanticized gun culture, we collectively go “wow sad that another batch of kids died, but how can I find this fascinating instead of just horrific”

The answer to “where did he go wrong” lies, as ever, at the foot of those who came before him. Systems and attitudes and actions which made him feel that he had to do this. Of course he made the choice, but the system which made him feel Ike he HAD that choice is unaccountable.

When one has reached a point of desperation that drives them to kill people, no matter the underlying cause, what could be more appealing than knowing two things:

1. Only a few people will remember the victims

2. Everyone will remember *me.*

This has been a present problem ever since Columbine.  Always dozens of articles obsessed with the identities of the perpetrators, and only a token journalistic glance at who the victims were. And that is exactly the WRONG message to send to anyone who is considering such an act.

STOP MAKING MASS MURDERERS FAMOUS. 

New York Post needs to knock that nonsense off. We don’t need to see nice family photos of the shooter. It helps nothing. Details of the event can be told without wondering “where did this nice boy go wrong” WHO CARES? 4 KIDS DIED.
